        <txttip left="935" top="46" right="1078" bottom="92" content="192.168.1.4&#x0D;&#x0A;255.255.255.0" fontname="Consolas" fontstyle="0" editsize="140" txtcolor="-16777216" txtbkcolor="-1" charset="1" />
        <txttip left="40" top="422" right="1336" bottom="621" content="Instructions:&#x0D;&#x0A;1. Configure the Name, IP address and subnet Mask for each device&#x0D;&#x0A;2. Test connectivity(using ping) between PC1 and PC3, PC1 and PC6. The devices should be able to reach each other&#x0D;&#x0A;3. On the switch, run the command &apos;display mac-address&apos; and analyse the mac address table of the switch.&#x0D;&#x0A;   from the result of the command, try to locate the MAC addresses of PC1, PC3 and PC6. Comfirm them with the actual Macs&#x0D;&#x0A;3. Open wireshark to capture packets at Eth0/0/3 of the Switch, then use PC3 to ping PC5,&#x0D;&#x0A;   take note of details of the first 5 packets that are exchanged(as captured by Wireshark)&#x0D;&#x0A;4. Save the complete work as &apos;Firstname-UserID-Lab2&apos;&#x0D;&#x0A;5. Zip the resulting folder(after saving) and add a saved data capture from (3) above) and upload the zip to the lms" fontname="Consolas" fontstyle="0" editsize="140" txtcolor="-16777216" txtbkcolor="-2044184" charset="1" />
    </txttips>
</topo>
